\begin{abstract}
Real-time data stream processing involves data structures and algorithms capable of performing efficiently under continuous, unlimited data input situations. To efficiently deal with constant and very fast data streams, one needs data structures that are able to cope with the three characteristics of being complex, adaptable, and very fast in computation at the same time. Static data structures cannot cope with scenarios that involve an infinite number of inserts, deletions, and updates happening at the same time. This paper presents the comparative study of twenty algorithms and data structures that are real time applicable for data stream processing, focusing on their theoretical design and empirical performance. The techniques selected include probabilistic sketches, adaptive classifiers, sliding-window models, clustering structures, and graph-based stream maintainers. 

The performance of every single algorithm is scrutinized under a common testing framework and it is done using Apache Flink and Kafka Streams. The evaluation takes into account both theoretical as well as empirical dimensions, i.e., analyzes the asymptotic time and space complexity along with latency, throughput, memory consumption and adaptability to dynamic data distributions. The findings show that the probabilistic structures require almost no operation time with logarithmic space requirements whereas the adaptive learners and drift detectors exhibit considerable tolerance to concept drift by allowing incremental model evolution. Moreover, the clustering and the graph-based structures have also proved their capability of being scalable for the multi-dimensional and topological analysis of the streams. In general, the study emphasizes the fundamental trade-offs among the factors of structural compactness, computational overhead, and learning adaptability, which, in turn, give the insights for algorithmic design and also the practical guidelines for the selection of the optimum DSAs in the areas of real-time analytics, IoT, and streaming-based computing systems.

\end{abstract}
