\section{Introduction}
The vast amount of data from IoT sensors, social networks, e-commerce platforms, and high-frequency transaction streams has converted computing into a data-driven ecosystem. Modern applications like online fraud detection, network monitoring, and intelligent transportation require real-time analytics on unbounded streams, as opposed to traditional batch-processing systems that handle finite datasets. The fundamental difficulty in this paradigm is building data structures and algorithms  that can retain dynamic states with little latency and memory overhead while providing predictable performance under high-velocity applications.Real-time stream processing differs greatly from traditional static data management methods. Batch systems schedule and execute computations after collecting all data. Data streams are ephemeral, with elements arriving sequentially and only being reviewed once. This restriction renders standard static structures like arrays, heaps, and trees ineffective when dealing with unexpected data and rapid updates. Static DSAs, designed for random access and stable datasets, struggle to handle volatile, high-volume, and time-dependent streaming data. Data stream processing necessitates specific structural designs that prioritize compactness, constant-time operations, and incremental adaptability to changing input.


Researchers have come up with stream-optimised data structures to solve the problem, which they call the accuracy-scalability trade-off. For instance, probabilistic sketches also known as Bloom Filter, Count-Min Sketch, or HyperLogLog can insert and query with almost the same speed and require very little space. Among the mechanisms used for temporal relevance maintenance, sliding-window is the popular one which is carried out by sustaining a finite active segment of the stream utilizing fixed, time-based or damped-weight strategies. On the other hand, adaptive algorithms like Hoeffding Tree, Adaptive Random Forest and Leveraging Bagging, will have the classical machine-learning structures working in an incremental manner, building models that evolve with the influx of new examples. Besides, drift-detection approaches such as ADWIN, DDM, and EDDM will perform monitoring of the system's performance, with a statistical basis, and will also determine when the concept has changed and trigger model updates. Moreover, the clustering methods like DenStream and StreamKM++ aim at retaining density info in constantly changing data distributions, and graph-stream algorithms keep the live connectivity among the evolving nodes. However, the comparison of structural techniques remains to be limited quantitatively across categories. Most of the existing studies point to the benchmark distributed frameworks such as Apache Flink, Spark Streaming and Kafka, with the architecture being the only subject of comparison while the internal data structures remain in the background. Consequently, a linear analysis has not been made that directly connects the memory footprint, asymptotic complexity and adaptive accuracy of the basic algorithms under identical experimental conditions. It is this lack of structural benchmarking that inspires the current research which intends to undertake a systematic evaluation of a wide-ranging collection of twenty data structures and algorithms for real-time data stream processing that are extensively employed.

The study that was put forward classifies algorithms into six categories probabilistic sketches, sliding-window models, drift-detectors, adaptive learners, stream-clustering algorithms, and graph-processing structures and their effectiveness is compared through a controlled experimental pipeline that is implemented in Apache Flink and Kafka Streams. The performance of each algorithm is evaluated along four key metrics, which are: latency, throughput, memory consumption, and accuracy, in addition to drift-adaptation delay that denotes the system's responsiveness to distributional changes. The experimental datasets generated from real-time IoT sensors data, financial transactions data, and social media feeds data, are providing realistic operating conditions.

In this thorough assessment, the study intends to answer three main research questions:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Which data structure provides the most suitable trade-off between time complexity and memory usage for real-time analytics?
    \item What is the impact of structural adaptability on accuracy during concept drift?
    \item Are hybrid structures that combine probabilistic and adaptive DSAs capable of delivering higher throughput while maintaining model performance?
\end{enumerate}

The key takeaways from this paper can be summarized as follows:

\begin{itemize}
    \item A comprehensive classification of data structures for streaming, organized by their design principles and operational complexities.
    \item A unified comparison framework derived from empirical experiments that measures end-to-end performance across heterogeneous algorithms.
    \item A statistical evaluation identifying correlations between structural design and computational efficiency.
    \item A collection of practical design guidelines for adopting optimal DSA combinations in real-time processing frameworks.
\end{itemize}


