\section{Related Work}

The processing of real-time data streams is the leading edge of the technology spectrum and has become a vital area in both industrial and research applications. This has been made possible by the massive growth of high-velocity data coming from various sources such as IoT sensors, networks, financial markets, and online applications. Recent large-scale reviews and comparative studies point out that there is an urgent need for specialized algorithms and data structures capable of efficiently supporting low-latency processing, adaptability, and robust memory management in streaming environments~\cite{bhatia2025survey}. 

A comprehensive survey by Bhatia \textit{et al.} (2025) brings into sharp focus the advancement in the use of probabilistic sketches, windowing models, adaptive classifiers, and drift detection methods while also discussing the strengths and limitations of different techniques such as Bloom Filters, Count-Min Sketch, KLL Sketch, HyperLogLog, and Top-$k$ structures for frequency, quantile, and distinct-count estimation in streaming contexts~\cite{bhatia2025survey}.

In stream analytics, window management techniques such as time-based, fixed-size, and adaptive windows (like ADWIN) remain essential for temporal relevance. Windowing is used in contemporary systems to maximize event-time accuracy and system scalability in addition to state management. To maintain model correctness despite changing data patterns, adaptive drift detectors such as DDM, EDDM, and ADWIN are being increasingly adopted in production systems. These detectors frequently outperform static threshold-based techniques~\cite{huang2024drift}.

In the field of adaptive learning, decision trees with very fast decision making (VFDT or Hoeffding Trees), ensemble forests, and bagging frameworks have shown strong performance for incremental learning while maintaining high classification accuracy even under unlimited stream length and frequent concept drift. Among others, Bayesian methods including online Gaussian Naive Bayes remain preferred for their quick updates and probabilistic decision-making efficiency. 

For unsupervised streaming tasks, clustering algorithms such as DenStream, CluStream, and StreamKM++ have been established as leading methods capable of tracking changes in data distributions over time~\cite{martin2025performance}. The most recent platform comparisons highlight the complementary relationship between data structure design and distributed stream-processing frameworks. The works of Wang and He and Martin  benchmark systems such as Apache Flink, Spark Structured Streaming, and Kafka Streams, revealing that the selection of underlying algorithms and data structures directly affects throughput, latency, and fault tolerance.

Despite the widespread adoption of advanced stream-processing frameworks, a unified experimental setup integrating data structure design, drift adaptation, and computational complexity evaluation under identical streaming workloads remains missing. This gap motivates the present study, which emphasizes structured and empirical benchmarking of twenty distinct data structures and algorithms bridging the divide between theoretical design and real-world stream analytics.


