\section{Taxonomy and Classification of Data Structures}
%===========================================================

\subsection{Overview of Streaming Data Structure Taxonomy}
Depending on the goals of the application, such as memory footprint, latency tolerance, and flexibility in response to changing input distributions, streaming data structures display different design philosophies.  While some concentrate on adaptive learning or temporal windowing, others give priority on probabilistic space efficiency.
 This study divides the twenty chosen algorithms into six functional families Probabilistic Sketches, Sliding Window Models, Adaptive Learning Structures, Drift Detection Mechanisms, Stream Clustering Structures, and Graph Stream Structures in order to methodically assess their contributions to real-time processing.
 This taxonomy offers a logical framework for comprehending their computational trade-offs, operational principles, and applicability for real-world implementation.

%-----------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{B. Functional Categories}

\subsubsection{Probabilistic Sketches}
By preserving approximations of enormous data streams, probabilistic sketch-based structures such as the \textit{Bloom Filter}, \textit{Count-Min Sketch}, \textit{HyperLogLog}, and \textit{Count Sketch} allow for constant-time operations and sublinear space utilization. They are typically used in duplicate detection systems, IoT telemetry, and network monitoring. These techniques are especially useful in edge and embedded environments because they achieve high throughput while conserving memory through controlled error bounds.
\vspace{1em}

\subsubsection{Sliding Window Models}
By ensuring that only the most recent data is included in analytics, sliding window techniques including \textit{Fixed Window}, \textit{Damped Window}, \textit{Time-based Window}, and \textit{Landmark Window} maintain temporal relevance. In real-time analytics, anomaly detection, and IoT time-series forecasting—where current data is more important than historical observations—these models are indispensable.
\vspace{1em}

\subsubsection{Adaptive Learning Structures}
The \textit{Hoeffding Tree}, \textit{Adaptive Random Forest (ARF)}, and \textit{Leveraging Bagging} are algorithms that belong to this group. They rely on incremental updates and are able to learn from streams that are continuously changing. Adaptive learners effectively handle concept drift while maintaining high predictive accuracy even in evolving environments—crucial for tasks such as spam filtering, credit scoring, and sensor-based fault prediction.
\vspace{1em}

\subsubsection{Drift Detection Mechanisms}
\textit{ADWIN}, \textit{DDM}, and \textit{EDDM} are drift detection frameworks that trace model error or distributional statistics to detect significant changes. They ensure analytical models remain aligned with the underlying data generation process. These algorithms are essential in domains that require continuous monitoring of changing data behavior, such as fraud detection and network intrusion prevention.
\vspace{1em}

\subsubsection{Stream Clustering Structures}
Techniques such as \textit{DenStream}, \textit{CluStream}, and \textit{StreamKM++} are responsible for dynamically grouping data elements in high-velocity streams. These methods employ micro-clustering and fading mechanisms to condense and retain recent trends while efficiently discarding outdated patterns. Applications include customer segmentation, evolving topic analysis, and event correlation in sensor networks.
\vspace{1em}

\subsubsection{ Graph Stream Structures}
Graph-oriented streaming algorithms such as \textit{Incremental PageRank}, \textit{Graph Reservoir Sampling}, and \textit{Sliding Window Graphs} focus on real-time preservation of graph topology evolution. These algorithms are optimized for efficiently measuring connectivity and edge statistics in large-scale, dynamic networks such as web graphs, communication logs, and social media interaction maps.


