\subsection{Windowing and Drift Detection Structures}
% ============================================================

Windowing techniques and drift-detection algorithms provide temporal control over data relevance and ensure adaptability under evolving distributions. 
Fixed-size or time-based sliding windows bound the active data horizon, while adaptive detectors such as ADWIN, DDM, and EDDM monitor model error to detect concept drift in real time.

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{7. Fixed-Size Sliding Window}

\textbf{Overview:}
A fixed-size sliding window retains the most recent $W$ elements in a continuous stream, discarding the oldest entry upon each insertion. 
This mechanism ensures constant memory utilization and enables timely analytics over the latest observations. 
Commonly used in traffic monitoring, streaming averages, and recent-trend tracking, it underlies many streaming frameworks like Apache Flink and Storm.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Fixed-Size Sliding Window Maintenance}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Insert}{$x$}
    \If{$|Window| = W$}
        \State remove oldest element
    \EndIf
    \State append $x$ to Window
\EndProcedure
\Procedure{ComputeAverage}{}
    \State \Return $\frac{1}{|Window|}\sum_{x \in Window} x$
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Insertion: $O(1)$; Query (e.g., average): $O(W)$ or $O(1)$ with incremental maintenance.  
Space: $O(W)$.  
Reference: [13]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{8. Time-Based Sliding Window}

\textbf{Overview:}
Unlike fixed-size windows, time-based windows retain elements within a temporal interval $T$ rather than a fixed count. 
This allows natural handling of irregular arrival rates in real-world streams such as sensor data or event logs. 
Frameworks like Kafka Streams and Flink use time-based windows for event-time alignment, aggregation, and trend analysis.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Time-Based Sliding Window Maintenance}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Insert}{$(x,t)$}
    \State append $(x,t)$ to Window
    \While{$t - Window[0].time > T$}
        \State remove oldest element
    \EndWhile
\EndProcedure
\Procedure{Aggregate}{}
    \State compute metric over valid elements
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Insertion: amortized $O(1)$; Expiration: $O(1)$ per element;  
Space: proportional to active events in window duration $T$.  
Reference: [14]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{9. ADWIN (Adaptive Windowing)}

\textbf{Overview:}
ADWIN dynamically resizes its window to detect concept drift by monitoring changes in the average of recent observations. 
When two subwindows exhibit statistically different means (using Hoeffding bounds), older data are discarded to adapt to new trends. 
It is widely adopted in adaptive learning pipelines and stream-mining frameworks like MOA.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{ADWIN Drift Detection Algorithm}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Update}{$x$}
    \State append $x$ to Window
    \While{there exists a split $W = W_0 + W_1$ s.t. $|mean(W_0) - mean(W_1)| > \epsilon_{cut}$}
        \State drop $W_0$ (older part)
    \EndWhile
\EndProcedure
\Procedure{DriftDetected}{}
    \State \Return True if reduction occurred
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Amortized $O(\log W)$ per update;  
Space: $O(W)$ dynamic window.  
Reference: [15]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{10. DDM (Drift Detection Method)}

\textbf{Overview:}
The Drift Detection Method (DDM) tracks model error rates in sequential predictions and signals a drift when the probability of error increases significantly beyond statistical expectation. 
It maintains mean and standard deviation of error probability, issuing warnings or drift alerts when thresholds are exceeded. 
DDM provides a lightweight, low-memory drift detector suited for embedded stream systems.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Drift Detection Method (DDM)}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Update}{$error\_t$}
    \State $p_t \gets \frac{\text{errors}}{t}$
    \State $s_t \gets \sqrt{p_t(1 - p_t)/t}$
    \If{$p_t + s_t > p_{min} + 3 s_{min}$}
        \State signal drift
    \ElsIf{$p_t + s_t > p_{min} + 2 s_{min}$}
        \State issue warning
    \EndIf
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Update: $O(1)$;  
Space: $O(1)$ (constant statistics).  
Reference: [16]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{11. EDDM (Early Drift Detection Method)}

\textbf{Overview:}
EDDM improves on DDM by focusing on the distance between errors rather than error rate itself, providing higher sensitivity to gradual drifts. 
By monitoring average distance between consecutive misclassifications, EDDM detects performance degradation earlier than DDM in non-stationary streams. 
It is often used in tandem with adaptive ensemble classifiers.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Early Drift Detection Method (EDDM)}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Update}{$d_t$}
    \State compute mean $\mu_t$ and std.\ deviation $\sigma_t$ of distances
    \If{$(\mu_t + 2\sigma_t)/(\mu_{max} + 2\sigma_{max}) < \alpha$}
        \State signal drift
    \EndIf
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Update: $O(1)$;  
Space: $O(1)$ statistics per stream.  
Reference: [17]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{12. Hoeffding Tree (VFDT)}

\textbf{Overview:}
The Hoeffding Tree (or Very Fast Decision Tree, VFDT) incrementally learns decision rules from data streams using the Hoeffding bound to determine statistically significant attribute splits. 
It processes each instance once, making it highly scalable for real-time classification under streaming constraints. 
VFDT forms the base learner for several adaptive ensemble algorithms.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Hoeffding Tree Incremental Learning}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Update}{$x, y$}
    \State route instance to corresponding leaf
    \State update class statistics
    \If{splitting criterion exceeds $\epsilon_{H}$}
        \State split leaf node on best attribute
    \EndIf
\EndProcedure
\Procedure{Predict}{$x$}
    \State traverse tree to predict class label
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Update: $O(\log N)$ per instance;  
Query: $O(\log N)$;  
Space: proportional to the number of leaves.  
Reference: [18]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ============================================================
\subsection{Adaptive Ensemble and Frequent Pattern Detection Structures}
% ============================================================

Ensemble-based models and pattern detectors enhance robustness and interpretability in evolving data streams. 
Adaptive ensembles combine drift-resilient base learners, while sketch-based frequent pattern detectors capture key elements or anomalies under strict memory constraints.

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{13. Adaptive Random Forest (ARF)}

\textbf{Overview:}
Adaptive Random Forest extends the traditional random forest to streaming data by integrating online bagging and drift adaptation. 
Each tree in the ensemble is trained incrementally using Hoeffding Trees as base learners, and outdated trees are replaced upon drift detection (e.g., via ADWIN). 
This ensures adaptability to both sudden and gradual concept drifts in large-scale stream classification.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Adaptive Random Forest Learning}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Update}{$x, y$}
    \For{each tree $T_i$ in ensemble}
        \State compute weight via Poisson(1)
        \State $T_i.\text{Update}(x, y)$
        \If{ADWIN detects drift}
            \State replace $T_i$ with new tree
        \EndIf
    \EndFor
\EndProcedure
\Procedure{Predict}{$x$}
    \State aggregate predictions from all trees
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Update: $O(k \log N)$;  
Prediction: $O(k \log N)$;  
Space: $O(k \times n_{nodes})$.  
Reference: [19]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{14. Online Bagging and Boosting}

\textbf{Overview:}
Online Bagging simulates bootstrap sampling for streaming data by drawing the number of replicates of each instance from a Poisson(1) distribution. 
Online Boosting reweights weak learners based on recent performance to emphasize difficult instances. 
These ensemble techniques maintain diversity and improve predictive accuracy without revisiting past data.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Online Bagging Procedure}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Update}{$x, y$}
    \For{each learner $L_i$}
        \State draw $k \sim \text{Poisson}(1)$
        \For{$j = 1$ to $k$}
            \State $L_i.\text{Update}(x, y)$
        \EndFor
    \EndFor
\EndProcedure
\Procedure{Predict}{$x$}
    \State return majority vote of all learners
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Update: $O(k)$;  
Prediction: $O(k)$;  
Space: $O(k \times m)$.  
Reference: [20]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{15. Stream Clustering using CluStream}

\textbf{Overview:}
CluStream partitions clustering into two phases: online micro-clustering and offline macro-clustering. 
It maintains micro-clusters summarizing recent data, which can later be merged or re-clustered for global insights. 
This structure provides scalable summarization for evolving data distributions in sensor, IoT, or traffic data streams.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{CluStream Online Phase}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Insert}{$x_t$}
    \If{nearest micro-cluster exists}
        \State update cluster statistics
    \Else
        \State create new micro-cluster
    \EndIf
    \If{time $\mod$ snapshotInterval = 0}
        \State store snapshot
    \EndIf
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Insertion: $O(k)$;  
Snapshot creation: $O(k)$;  
Space: $O(kd)$ for $k$ clusters and $d$ dimensions.  
Reference: [21]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{16. DenStream (Density-Based Stream Clustering)}

\textbf{Overview:}
DenStream extends DBSCAN to streaming contexts by maintaining core micro-clusters with temporal fading. 
It distinguishes between potential and outlier micro-clusters based on density thresholds and updates them incrementally. 
This makes it effective for identifying evolving dense regions in non-stationary streams.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{DenStream Online Maintenance}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Insert}{$x_t$}
    \State decay weights of all clusters
    \If{within $\epsilon$ of existing core cluster}
        \State update cluster statistics
    \Else
        \State create new outlier cluster
    \EndIf
    \State periodically merge or remove clusters below threshold
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Update: $O(k)$;  
Merge/prune: amortized $O(k)$;  
Space: $O(k)$.  
Reference: [22]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{17. Lossy Counting}

\textbf{Overview:}
Lossy Counting is an approximate frequency-counting algorithm that guarantees error bounds in tracking frequent items from streams. 
It partitions the stream into buckets and periodically removes items with low estimated frequencies, ensuring sublinear memory usage. 
Used widely for web log analysis, trending item tracking, and frequency estimation under resource limits.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Lossy Counting Algorithm}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Process}{$x$}
    \If{$x$ in table}
        \State increment $count(x)$
    \Else
        \State insert $x$ with $count=1$, $\Delta = bucketID-1$
    \EndIf
    \If{bucketID \mod 1/\epsilon = 0}
        \State remove items with $count + \Delta \le bucketID$
    \EndIf
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Insertion: amortized $O(1)$;  
Space: $O(\frac{1}{\epsilon})$.  
Reference: [23]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{18. Space-Saving Algorithm}

\textbf{Overview:}
The Space-Saving algorithm improves upon Lossy Counting by maintaining a fixed number $k$ of counters. 
Each new element either increments an existing counter or replaces the minimum-count item, keeping frequent elements approximated accurately. 
It’s efficient for detecting heavy hitters in streaming data such as trending hashtags or URLs.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Space-Saving Heavy Hitter Detection}

\Procedure{Process}{$x$}
    \If{$x$ in table}
        \State increment count
    \Else
        \State replace item with minimum count
        \State set new count = old min + 1
    \EndIf
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Update: $O(1)$;  
Space: $O(k)$.  
Reference: [24]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{19. Sketch-Based Anomaly Detection (Count Sketch)}

\textbf{Overview:}
Count Sketch maintains multiple hash-based counters with signed updates to estimate both frequency and direction of deviation. 
By computing variance of hashed counts, it enables efficient anomaly detection or rare-event estimation. 
Commonly used for identifying network anomalies or rare behaviors in high-speed streams.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Count Sketch Update and Query}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Update}{$x, c$}
    \For{$i = 1$ to $d$}
        \State $C[i, h_i(x)] \gets C[i, h_i(x)] + s_i(x)c$
    \EndFor
\EndProcedure
\Procedure{Estimate}{$x$}
    \State \Return median over $i$ of $s_i(x) \times C[i, h_i(x)]$
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Update: $O(d)$;  
Query: $O(d)$;  
Space: $O(d \times w)$.  
Reference: [25]
\end{tcolorbox}

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\noindent\textbf{20. Frequent Pattern Stream Miner (FP-Stream)}

\textbf{Overview:}
FP-Stream is an incremental adaptation of FP-Growth designed for continuous transaction streams. 
It maintains an in-memory prefix tree with fading factors, pruning infrequent nodes as data evolves. 
This allows mining of evolving frequent itemsets or patterns with limited memory and without revisiting historical data.

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{FP-Stream Incremental Update}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{InsertTransaction}{$T$}
    \For{each item $i \in T$}
        \State insert $i$ into FP-Tree path
        \State update frequency count with fading factor
    \EndFor
    \State periodically prune nodes below support threshold
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Time Complexity:}  
Insertion: $O(|T|)$;  
Pruning: amortized $O(n)$;  
Space: proportional to active frequent itemsets.  
Reference: [26]
\end{tcolorbox}


\section{Comparative Analysis of Algorithms}

\subsection{Overview}
Twenty top algorithms and data structures for real-time stream processing are thoroughly compared in this part based on factors including memory usage, temporal complexity, and flexibility to accommodate changing data streams.  The analysis offers practitioners comprehensive trade-off insights by referencing recent empirical benchmarks and theoretical research in the literature. 

\subsection{Comparative Dimensions}

\subsubsection{Time Complexity}
Probabilistic Sketches (\textit{Bloom Filter}, \textit{Count-Min Sketch}, \textit{HyperLogLog}, \textit{Count Sketch}, \textit{Cuckoo Filter}): Most sketch-based data structures achieve extremely fast $O(1)$ update and query operations, attributed to highly optimized hash-based indexing mechanisms. This enables real-time ingestion of millions of events in streaming environments \cite{cao2023high, zeng2023double}. 
\noindent Sliding Window Models (\textit{Fixed}, \textit{Damped}, \textit{Time-Based}, \textit{Landmark}): These models often operate linearly with window size, typically $O(w)$, since maintaining or querying entries may involve scanning or shifting data.  

\noindent Adaptive Learning Structures (\textit{Hoeffding Tree}, \textit{Adaptive Random Forest}, \textit{Leveraging Bagging}, \textit{Gaussian Naive Bayes}): Generally exhibit $O(\log n)$ complexity for incremental updates or predictions, providing strong support for online learning and concept drift adaptation \cite{vazquez2023comparison}.  

\noindent Drift Detection Mechanisms (\textit{ADWIN}, \textit{DDM}, \textit{EDDM}): Typically operate in $O(1)$ time for drift checks, but may reach $O(n)$ during statistical evaluation phases, depending on stream size and drift intensity \cite{komorniczak2023complexity}.  

\noindent Stream Clustering Algorithms (\textit{DenStream}, \textit{CluStream}, \textit{StreamKM++}): The update complexity scales with the number of clusters and dimensionality, represented as $O(k \cdot d)$, with occasional spikes during cluster merging.  

\noindent Graph Stream Structures (\textit{Incremental Connectivity}, \textit{PageRank}): The update cost can grow to $O(E)$ or higher as edge relationships increase, particularly in dense dynamic graphs.

\vspace{0.5em}
\subsubsection{Space Efficiency}
\noindent \textbf{Sketches:} These employ sublinear or logarithmic space $O(\log n)$, enabling deployment under stringent memory constraints in edge and IoT contexts.  
\noindent \textbf{Sliding Windows:} Memory usage grows linearly with window length, typically $O(w)$.  
\noindent \textbf{Learners \& Detectors:} Space complexity depends on model structure—$O(n)$ for decision trees and ensembles, whereas drift detectors maintain compact summaries with $O(1)$ memory footprints.  
\noindent \textbf{Clustering:} Requires $O(k)$ space to store micro-clusters efficiently.  
\noindent \textbf{Graphs:} Space requirements can reach $O(V + E)$, which may become limiting in massive real-time networks.

\vspace{0.5em}
\subsubsection{Flexibility}
\noindent \textbf{Drift Detectors and Adaptive Learners:} Inherently adaptive, these systems react dynamically to distributional shifts and concept drift without requiring manual intervention.  
\noindent \textbf{Sketches and Windows:} Generally static in nature, necessitating external adjustments such as window resizing or parameter re-tuning for adaptive responsiveness.  
\noindent \textbf{Clustering and Graph Structures:} Capable of dynamic adaptability when implemented with incremental update logic, fading factors, or edge re-weighting, thus enabling continuous tracking of evolving systems \cite{komorniczak2023complexity, cao2023high}.
 

