\subsection{Domain-Specific Recommendations}

\noindent \textbf{IoT and Edge Devices:} Under strict resource constraints, lightweight sketch-based data structures are recommended for simple summarization, anomaly detection, and duplicate filtering. These probabilistic methods offer minimal memory usage and ultra-low latency, making them ideal for embedded and edge analytics scenarios.

\vspace{0.3em}
\noindent \textbf{Real-Time Analytics:} For temporal pattern mining and short-term event detection, a hybrid combination of sliding window models and adaptive clustering algorithms is most effective. This enables real-time systems to retain temporal relevance while adapting dynamically to variations in streaming input behavior.

\vspace{0.3em}
\noindent \textbf{Changing Systems:} In highly dynamic data environments, drift detectors coupled with ensemble learners (such as Hoeffding Trees and Adaptive Random Forests) preserve predictive accuracy amid continuous concept drift. These combinations are best suited for online fraud monitoring, intrusion detection, and adaptive recommendation systems.

\vspace{0.3em}
\noindent \textbf{Big Graph and Social Networks:} Large-scale dynamic networks such as social media interaction graphs or urban IoT sensor networks benefit significantly from incremental graph algorithms. Techniques like incremental PageRank and sliding window graph maintenance enable efficient real-time tracking of evolving connectivity and relationship patterns.



\section{Time Complexity Based on Application}

\subsection{ IoT and Edge Analytics}

Edge computing and sensor networks operate under extremely tight latency constraints often below a few milliseconds per event. Data structures such as the  and  are highly suitable for these environments, as they provide constant-time ($O(1)$) insertion and query operations with very low memory consumption.

Similarly,{HyperLogLog} and {Cuckoo Filter} offer efficient solutions for approximate counting and deduplication, making them particularly valuable for bandwidth-limited edge devices . 
However, adaptive learners such as the \textit{Hoeffding Tree} and other incremental classifiers tend to be computationally heavier; thus, they are better suited for gateway-level analytics where slightly higher latency can be tolerated in exchange for improved adaptive accuracy .

\subsection{Real-Time Financial Analytics}

Financial data streams such as stock tick updates, transaction logs, and credit risk signals require sub-second decision-making capabilities along with adaptive drift handling. Algorithms like the \textit{Adaptive Random Forest (ARF)} and drift detectors based on \textit{ADWIN} achieve an optimal balance between logarithmic update time ($O(\log n)$) and high adaptability in rapidly evolving markets \cite{komorniczak2023drift}. 
Although these models are computationally more demanding than probabilistic sketches, they consistently deliver superior predictive accuracy under non-stationary financial conditions. 
Recent empirical studies also demonstrate that hybrid architectures—combining lightweight sketches for real-time event summarization with adaptive ensemble models for decision making attain near optimal throughput and latency trade-offs in large-scale financial analytics platforms .

\subsection{Network and Cybersecurity Monitoring}

The analysis of network traffic demands instantaneous classification and large-scale anomaly detection. Probabilistic sketch-based structures such as the \textit{Count-Min Sketch (CMS)} and the \textit{Count Sketch} are particularly effective for identifying heavy hitters and estimating frequency in packet streams operating at multi-million update rates per second. Their constant-time processing cost ($O(1)$) enables their deployment in routers, firewalls, and intrusion detection systems with limited computational budgets . 

Conversely, ensemble-based classifiers such as \textit{Leveraging Bagging}, though more memory-intensive, enhance adaptability to dynamic attack patterns. These models sustain competitive performance under evolving traffic distributions, achieving reliable classification at a logarithmic computational cost of $O(\log n)$ . 

\vspace{0.3em}
\subsection{Social and Graph Stream Applications}

The structure and interaction dynamics of social and communication networks evolve continuously, requiring efficient algorithms capable of tracking changes in real time. Graph-based streaming algorithms such as \textit{Incremental PageRank}, \textit{Sliding Window Graphs}, and \textit{Graph Reservoir Sampling} support update operations at a complexity of $O(E)$, where $E$ represents the number of active edges in the network . 

While these methods demand considerable computational resources, they remain indispensable for tasks such as influence propagation analysis, community detection, and real-time connectivity monitoring. Recent distributed implementations have significantly reduced effective update latency by parallelizing edge updates and local rank computations across multiple streaming partitions, thus improving scalability and responsiveness in large-scale graph processing environments .


\subsection{Comparative Insights}
 Algorithmic suitability is more dependent on workload factors than asymptotic complexity, according to the cross-domain examination.  The optimum compromise is provided by constant-time sketching for embedded or ultra-low-latency Internet of Things systems.
 Even while adaptive learners and rift detectors have a higher time complexity, they are crucial for analytical contexts like cybersecurity or finance where accuracy under drift is crucial.
 Even though graph-stream algorithms are computationally intensive, they are still the best at managing dynamic relationships in web and social data.  Thus, this domain-oriented mapping of temporal complexity offers a useful foundation for choosing data structures that support operational objectives in real time.

