\section{Discussion}

The comparative evaluation reveals significant differences
among the data-structure families when it comes to com-
putation efficiency, flexibility, and applicability in real-time. Probabilistic
sketches like Bloom Filter, Count-Min Sketch, and Hyper-
LogLog have the lowest latency and memory usage,
with $O(1)$ update time and sublinear space consumption,
the whole time. Their ease of use and fast operation make
them perfect for edge analytics, telemetry aggregation, and
duplicate suppression where strict memory budgets are in place
\cite{zeng2023double}. Nonetheless, they unavoidably give up exactness and
cannot adapt to changing data distributions, which
makes them unsuitable for contexts where accuracy or
long-term pattern tracking is required.

On the other hand, the adaptive learning structures such as
Hoeffding Tree, Adaptive Random Forest (ARF), and 
Leveraging Bagging are very resilient in the presence of 
non-stationary data. Their incremental nature allows 
continuous model updates without having to train from 
scratch, and even under abrupt concept drift they still 
achieve high predictive accuracy \cite{komorniczak2023complexity}. However, the computational costs that come with having multiple 
evolving learners for updates are the factors that 
increase both latency and energy consumption making them 
unfit for low-power or edge devices.


Sliding-window models are the means between adaptability and efficiency. They keep temporal relevance but need frequent updates and deletions which makes their computational load depend on the window size linearly. They can be paired with clustering techniques such as DenStream or StreamKM++ to provide powerful temporal analytics but they are still affected by data drift in long-running streams.

Drift detection methods like ADWIN and DDM help by providing statistical triggers for model updates to the adaptive learners. These detectors allow for very detailed responsiveness to changes in input distributions and this greatly enhances the stability of streaming models \cite{vazquez2023comparison}. However, if the threshold parameters are not adjusted perfectly, the frequent drift alarms can lead to unnecessary retraining overhead.

Graph-stream structures (Incremental PageRank, Graph Reservoir Sampling) are very complicated but are still the necessary tools for social network analysis, web graph evolution, and streaming connectivity systems. Their ability to perform dynamic topology maintenance in real-time is second to none, but the cost is the memory which is proportional to the number of vertices and edges.

From a general viewpoint, hybrid configurations mixing sketches for data summarization with adaptive learners and drift detectors for incremental intelligence are the most balanced solution. For example, a Count-Min Sketch together with an Adaptive Random Forest can provide both efficiency and adaptability, thus allowing real-time classification in IoT networks with limited resources. The comparative insights hence point out that there is no single structure that excels in all metrics; rather, the choice depends on the operational priorities of the streaming environment.




\section{Research Gap}

Data stream algorithms have advanced quickly, however there are still a number of important research gaps:

\subsection{Research Gaps}

Despite substantial advancements in streaming data structure design and evaluation, several open issues remain to be addressed in current literature. The major research gaps identified are as follows:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Lack of Unified Benchmarks:} Existing studies primarily evaluate distributed frameworks such as \textit{Apache Flink}, \textit{Spark Streaming}, and \textit{Kafka Streams}, rather than the internal data structures that drive their performance. There are very few standardized benchmarking setups capable of assessing algorithmic efficiency under identical streaming workloads.
    
    \item \textbf{Limited Hybrid Architectures:} There is a notable scarcity of architectures that tightly integrate probabilistic and adaptive mechanisms within a single implementation. The synergy between approximate counting structures and incremental learning algorithms remains largely unexplored for high-throughput, low-latency environments.
    
    \item \textbf{Neglect of Energy and Hardware Constraints:} Most experimental evaluations rely on high-end, server-grade hardware. In contrast, edge computing environments—such as IoT and vehicular systems—require lightweight and energy-efficient streaming algorithms optimized for ARM-based and embedded processors.
    
    \item \textbf{Underrepresentation of Domain-Specific Applications:} While network monitoring and financial analytics have received substantial attention, domains such as transportation systems, environmental monitoring, and smart-city infrastructure remain underexplored in real-time streaming research \cite{cao2023high}
    
    \item \textbf{Inadequate Drift-Resilient Metrics:} Conventional performance measures—such as accuracy, latency, and throughput—fail to capture drift-reactivity and adaptation delay, both of which are critical indicators of a model’s long-term stability and responsiveness in dynamic streaming environments.
\end{itemize}

Filling these research gaps will not only enhance the robustness and adaptability of streaming analytics but will also promote architectural optimizations that evolve toward structurally intelligent, self-adaptive data systems.




\section{Future Directions and Open Challenges}

Future research must concentrate on using cross-disciplinary innovations to improve the interpretability, energy efficiency, and adaptability of real-time data structures:

\subsection{Hybrid and Self-Optimizing Structures}
Emerging research trends point toward the development of hybrid data structures that seamlessly integrate sketches, sliding windows, and adaptive models. Systems leveraging probabilistic summarization as a pre-processing layer—followed by adaptive learners—can dynamically balance throughput and learning accuracy. A promising architectural avenue is the design of self-tuning mechanisms capable of autonomously adjusting key parameters such as hash depth or window length in response to fluctuating workloads. Such self-optimizing DSAs would minimize human intervention while ensuring sustained real-time efficiency.

\vspace{0.3em}
\subsection{BEnergy-Aware and Edge-Optimized DSAs}
With the exponential rise of IoT and vehicular data, there is an urgent demand for low-power, memory-efficient data structures. Approaches incorporating compressed counters, bit-level optimization, and quantized learning models can significantly reduce energy consumption while maintaining acceptable accuracy. Future research must focus on optimizing DSAs for ARM-based processors and edge accelerators, enabling sustainable and scalable real-time analytics across constrained environments.

\vspace{0.3em}
\subsection{C. Federated and Privacy-Preserving Streaming}
Privacy and data governance have become pivotal challenges in distributed real-time analytics. Future DSA designs should emphasize federated streaming approaches that perform local computations and periodically synchronize compact summaries to maintain global insights without centralizing raw data. Techniques such as lightweight encryption, differential privacy, and homomorphic hashing present promising directions for achieving secure and efficient real-time data sharing across organizational and geographical boundaries.

\vspace{0.3em}
\subsection{D. Interpretable and Explanatory Stream Models}
Interpretability remains a major challenge in continuous learning systems. To foster trust and accountability in automated decision-making, future streaming algorithms must incorporate transparent, human-understandable explanations of model updates, drift detections, and predictions. Integrating explainable AI (XAI) principles into data stream algorithms can bridge the gap between algorithmic performance and interpretability.

\vspace{0.3em}
\subsection{E. Frameworks for Standardized Benchmarking}
The research community urgently requires open-source, cross-platform benchmark suites to facilitate uniform comparisons of streaming algorithms under consistent conditions—covering hardware configurations, input velocity, and dataset characteristics. Establishing standardized benchmarking frameworks and visualization dashboards for latency, drift, and throughput metrics will ensure reproducibility, promote transparency, and encourage inter-institutional collaboration in the domain of real-time data stream analytics.


\section{Conclusion}

This research work provides an extensive comparative study of 
twenty different data structures along with algorithms for 
real-time data stream processing and grouped them into six 
functional categories. Theoretical and empirical evaluation 
showed that probabilistic sketches are very effective in terms of 
cost, but adaptive learners and drift detectors surpass in terms 
of accuracy and resistance to changing data distributions. 
Clustering and graph-based structures, although more complex in 
terms of computation, are still crucial for sophisticated 
relational and temporal stream analytics.

The main takeaway from this study is that the performance of 
algorithms in streaming environments does not rely on absolute 
dominance but rather on their proper alignment with the 
application's goals speed, accuracy, or adaptability being 
the key ones. Thus, hybrid combinations of lightweight 
probabilistic techniques with adaptive learners and drift 
detectors are seen as the most evenly matched solution.

To sum up, the current work lays down a framework 
and a comparison for the selection, application and 
future design of data structures optimized for streaming 
applications. The future research into hybrid, self-optimizing 
and energy-efficient DSA will be a substantial 
step towards the creation of next-generation, smart, and 
sustainable real-time data processing ecosystems.




